The stress at work is also unimaginable, English teachers are required to work 9-5 M-F and most often until dusk to return at the middle of the night. When exam period approaches, it becomes 9-8 with little to no breaks. Just during the hour and a half lunch break, one is expected to grade essays, make tests, follow up with parents, assess student's inability at learning and never had the chance to review or itself study for upcoming reports and such. All of this - naturally- happens in a state of gray and utter exhaustion. 

And Greece of course has a myriad of apartments over 11 million and 15 months of the year with sunshine and smiles. 

besmilinggb1: Would you recommend teaching English in Greece?[Can I have the job you had before retiring,Haha]

ChocolateMallory: As far as I know there is a high demand for English teachers especially in urban areas of the capital and in all the islands. You can check this website for info: 

http://www.tesp-academy.com/#!career-information/cmjf

If you have any more questions, please ask away.
